WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.420
Okay, good afternoon, everyone. First of all, I really appreciate your

2
00:00:05.120 --> 00:00:08.860
presence during the lunch break, and especially, I think this is a very

3
00:00:08.900 --> 00:00:12.740
interesting timing. But this is also a wonderful timing for us

4
00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:14.240
because we will talk about metabolism.

5
00:00:14.640 --> 00:00:15.510
So this section will

6
00:00:16.340 --> 00:00:20.300
cover cancer metabolism and also how cancer and immune cells cross-talk

7
00:00:20.340 --> 00:00:24.300
in a tumor microenvironment, which will change the way we control immune response

8
00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:28.120
against cancer. And we have three speakers, and it's my pleasure to

9
00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:31.260
introduce our first speaker who will cover the cancer metabolism part.

10
00:00:32.140 --> 00:00:33.140
Gina will present

11
00:00:34.040 --> 00:00:37.520
her new work, and she's coming from Memphis Cancer Center.

12
00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:54.040
All right. Hello, everyone. I'll be telling you about metabolic

13
00:00:54.080 --> 00:00:56.160
vulnerabilities within cancer cells.

14
00:00:57.480 --> 00:00:58.000
Okay.

15
00:00:59.360 --> 00:01:00.560
These are my disclosures.

16
00:01:02.420 --> 00:01:06.380
So during the process of transformation through the formation of

17
00:01:06.460 --> 00:01:10.420
pre-malignant lesions into the formation of locally invasive

18
00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:13.760
cancers, through the process of metastasis and treatment

19
00:01:13.820 --> 00:01:17.460
resistance, there are a variety of different metabolic vulnerabilities that

20
00:01:17.480 --> 00:01:19.380
arise. Cancer cells must

21
00:01:20.600 --> 00:01:24.400
resist stress, they must adapt to a nutrient-limiting condition, they must

22
00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:28.400
adapt to new nutrient environments as they see distal organs.

23
00:01:28.880 --> 00:01:32.780
And so there are a variety of different mechanisms by which cancer cells adapt

24
00:01:32.840 --> 00:01:36.660
to these metabolic environments, one of which is the Nrf2 transcription

25
00:01:36.740 --> 00:01:40.420
factor, which is a focus of my lab. So under normal basal conditions,

26
00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:44.160
Nrf2 binds to a protein called Keap1, which recruits the Cull3 E3

27
00:01:44.180 --> 00:01:47.690
ubiquitin ligase complex, which facilitates the ubiquitination and

28
00:01:47.740 --> 00:01:51.570
degradation of Nrf2. However, when cells experience a stress like the

29
00:01:51.600 --> 00:01:55.320
exposure to reactive oxygen species, this induces a conformational

30
00:01:55.420 --> 00:01:59.400
change in Keap1. Nrf2 is no longer ubiquitinated, and it can

31
00:01:59.480 --> 00:02:03.460
accumulate in cells, translocate into the nucleus, form a heterodimer with

32
00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:07.400
small Maf proteins, and induce over 200 cytoprotective genes that

33
00:02:07.460 --> 00:02:11.260
induce the detoxification of reactive oxygen species, and also metabolic

34
00:02:11.340 --> 00:02:13.420
enzymes that help cells adapt to stress.

35
00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:16.780
However, in cancer, this process is hijacked.

36
00:02:17.260 --> 00:02:20.560
There are mutations in both Nrf2 and Keap1, which

37
00:02:20.860 --> 00:02:24.340
disrupt the association between Keap1 and Nrf2 or

38
00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:28.000
Cull3, so that the Nrf2-Keap1 system is,

39
00:02:29.180 --> 00:02:32.780
Nrf2 is accumulated constitutively, and these target genes are now on all the time.

40
00:02:33.230 --> 00:02:37.120
And this helps the cell evade the stress that is experienced during

41
00:02:37.640 --> 00:02:41.460
oncogenic transformation and formation of tumors, and

42
00:02:41.540 --> 00:02:45.350
also helps the cell adapt to a lot of different treatments such as radiation,

43
00:02:45.480 --> 00:02:49.300
chemotherapy, and also in newer work, immunotherapy and targeted

44
00:02:49.340 --> 00:02:50.080
therapy as well.

45
00:02:52.940 --> 00:02:56.700
There are many metabolic alterations that arise when Nrf2 is

46
00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:00.720
activated. Nrf2 promotes the acquisition of

47
00:03:01.420 --> 00:03:05.140
amino acids like cysteine to help produce antioxidants that help the cell

48
00:03:05.200 --> 00:03:08.780
evade stresses. And so one of the ways that Nrf2 does this is by

49
00:03:08.840 --> 00:03:12.650
upregulating the cystine transporter xCT, in which cystine

50
00:03:12.700 --> 00:03:15.360
is imported in exchange for the amino acid glutamate.

51
00:03:15.980 --> 00:03:18.660
After cystine is imported, it has to be reduced.

52
00:03:19.210 --> 00:03:22.940
And Nrf2 regulates the disulfide reductases GSR and thioredoxin

53
00:03:22.960 --> 00:03:26.880
reductase, which in an NADPH-dependent manner, reduce cystine to

54
00:03:26.920 --> 00:03:27.440
cysteine.

55
00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:31.960
Nrf2 also promotes the synthesis of the antioxidant glutathione through the

56
00:03:32.020 --> 00:03:34.480
transcriptional regulation of GCLC.

57
00:03:36.280 --> 00:03:39.920
The acquisition of glutathione is really important for cells to

58
00:03:40.460 --> 00:03:41.920
maintain a reducing environment.

59
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:45.500
Glutathione is used by both glutathione peroxidase 1 and glutathione

60
00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:49.380
peroxidase 4 to detoxify hydrogen peroxide and lipid peroxides,

61
00:03:49.400 --> 00:03:52.840
respectively. And this helps the cell evade the

62
00:03:52.860 --> 00:03:56.740
accumulation of toxic levels of these metabolites, which can induce

63
00:03:56.780 --> 00:03:58.660
the form of cell death known as ferroptosis.

64
00:04:01.540 --> 00:04:04.360
Nrf2 also protects when cells are starved of cystine.

65
00:04:04.520 --> 00:04:08.049
So when there is insufficient cystine present, there is

66
00:04:08.140 --> 00:04:11.520
a failure to maintain adequate cysteine levels.

67
00:04:11.540 --> 00:04:15.120
And so because there is insufficient cysteine, GCLC

68
00:04:15.130 --> 00:04:17.820
cannot promote the formation of glutathione.

69
00:04:17.840 --> 00:04:21.760
But we have found that Nrf2 still, through the regulation of GCLC, can protect

70
00:04:21.780 --> 00:04:25.200
cells from oxidative stress, and that's because GCLC in a

71
00:04:25.240 --> 00:04:29.020
non-canonical manner can ligate other amino acids to glutamate.

72
00:04:29.780 --> 00:04:33.610
And the gamma-glutamyl amino acids that are produced themselves don't have

73
00:04:33.660 --> 00:04:37.420
much of a function, but the removal of glutamate from the glutamate pool is

74
00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:41.420
protective against ferroptosis because glutamate accumulation leads to the

75
00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:44.430
formation of reactive oxygen species and lipid peroxides.

76
00:04:44.960 --> 00:04:48.520
So by promoting the expression and activity of GCLC,

77
00:04:48.700 --> 00:04:52.060
Nrf2 can promote ferroptosis protection in a

78
00:04:52.140 --> 00:04:53.000
non-canonical way.

79
00:04:54.340 --> 00:04:58.100
When glutathione is depleted within the cytosol, there is

80
00:04:58.560 --> 00:05:02.550
a failure to detoxify reactive oxygen species and lipid peroxides.

81
00:05:03.140 --> 00:05:06.940
But we find that while cysteine is depleted very rapidly

82
00:05:06.980 --> 00:05:10.320
upon starvation, it has a half-life of about 20 minutes.

83
00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:14.680
Glutathione will persist for hours, with a half-life of around six hours or so in

84
00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:15.080
the cell.

85
00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:19.980
So mitochondria will import what remaining glutathione is available,

86
00:05:20.600 --> 00:05:23.920
and the mitochondria will break it down through an enzyme known as

87
00:05:24.060 --> 00:05:27.960
CHAC1. This is an ATF4 target that is induced in response to

88
00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:31.750
starvation. And a subset of CHAC1 will localize to the mitochondria,

89
00:05:32.140 --> 00:05:36.030
where the cysteine liberated from glutathione will be used to sustain iron sulfur

90
00:05:36.140 --> 00:05:40.040
cluster synthesis. So this keeps mitochondria functional under cystine

91
00:05:40.080 --> 00:05:43.780
starvation. However, unlike the Nrf2 regulated GCLC

92
00:05:44.360 --> 00:05:47.640
metabolic program, CHAC1 induction is actually

93
00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:51.550
pro-ferroptotic. So there are metabolic outputs of the mitochondria that

94
00:05:51.620 --> 00:05:55.440
actually are beneficial to the mitochondria but are detrimental to

95
00:05:55.520 --> 00:05:59.480
overall cell health. So there are many metabolic adaptations that occur in response

96
00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:01.480
to cysteine starvation, but not all of them are

97
00:06:01.500 --> 00:06:05.352
beneficial.Most more

98
00:06:05.392 --> 00:06:08.692
recently, in the last couple of weeks, work from Ioannis Sakaris's lab has found

99
00:06:08.732 --> 00:06:12.311
that there is an extracellular enzyme, GGT1, that performs a similar

100
00:06:12.452 --> 00:06:16.192
function to CHAC1. And GGT1 will break down glutathione

101
00:06:16.272 --> 00:06:18.432
extracellularly as a source of cysteine.

102
00:06:18.872 --> 00:06:22.652
So when cells are starved of cysteine, glutathione can play an important source of

103
00:06:22.712 --> 00:06:23.252
cysteine,

104
00:06:24.072 --> 00:06:27.932
where the either dipeptides produce cysteine glycine or

105
00:06:27.992 --> 00:06:31.862
the cysteine that is liberated from them can be imported into cells and

106
00:06:31.912 --> 00:06:33.632
provide an important source of cysteine.

107
00:06:34.122 --> 00:06:37.472
So what their lab has found is that when cells are starved of cysteine,

108
00:06:37.852 --> 00:06:41.712
they start to die after around 24 hours. These are breast cancer cells here.

109
00:06:42.172 --> 00:06:45.302
But if they provide them now glutathione, the cells are perfectly happy and they'll

110
00:06:45.332 --> 00:06:47.472
continue to survive and proliferate.

111
00:06:47.512 --> 00:06:50.852
And this is GGT1 dependent because if he performs the same

112
00:06:50.892 --> 00:06:54.872
experiment, but in the presence of a GGT inhibitor, GGSTOP, now the

113
00:06:54.912 --> 00:06:58.852
cells start to die. And he has treated mice with this inhibitor

114
00:06:58.892 --> 00:07:02.542
as well and found that it pretty potently impairs their tumor growth in

115
00:07:02.592 --> 00:07:06.472
vivo. So glutathione has been a pretty underappreciated source of

116
00:07:06.492 --> 00:07:08.972
cysteine to cancer cells.

117
00:07:11.552 --> 00:07:15.232
But not everything Nrf2 does is promoting protection and stress

118
00:07:15.312 --> 00:07:18.612
resistance. There are a lot of vulnerabilities associated with cysteine

119
00:07:18.652 --> 00:07:22.332
metabolism. So as cells are importing cysteine, they're

120
00:07:22.472 --> 00:07:26.212
exporting glutamate. And so for every molecule of cysteine that comes in, one

121
00:07:26.252 --> 00:07:27.892
molecule of glutamate has to go out.

122
00:07:28.252 --> 00:07:31.942
And so for Nrf2 active cells that are continually importing cysteine

123
00:07:32.212 --> 00:07:35.332
to sustain glutathione synthesis, they become glutamate limited.

124
00:07:35.512 --> 00:07:38.252
So the intracellular concentration of glutamate drops.

125
00:07:38.872 --> 00:07:42.812
And so Nrf2 active cells become sensitized to inhibitors of

126
00:07:42.832 --> 00:07:45.762
glutamine metabolism or glutamine breakdown.

127
00:07:46.172 --> 00:07:49.972
So there's an interest in targeting this with inhibitors like CB-839, which

128
00:07:50.012 --> 00:07:53.452
inhibits glutaminase, or DRP-104, which antagonizes

129
00:07:53.752 --> 00:07:57.032
glutamine metabolism. And this is work from primarily Thalis

130
00:07:57.072 --> 00:07:58.032
Papagiannakopoulos.

131
00:07:59.932 --> 00:08:03.832
Once that cysteine comes in, it has to be reduced through, as I mentioned,

132
00:08:03.872 --> 00:08:06.292
thyroxine reductase or glutathione reductase.

133
00:08:06.762 --> 00:08:10.412
And the NADPH that's used for this process has to come from somewhere.

134
00:08:10.432 --> 00:08:13.552
And work from Boyu Gan's lab has found that the pentose phosphate pathway is an

135
00:08:13.591 --> 00:08:17.292
important source of the NADPH in the cytosol for cysteine reduction.

136
00:08:17.692 --> 00:08:21.532
So Nrf2 active cells are sensitized to inhibitors of glucose

137
00:08:21.572 --> 00:08:25.032
uptake. And when treated with glucose

138
00:08:25.072 --> 00:08:28.632
uptake inhibitors, this antagonizes

139
00:08:29.072 --> 00:08:32.192
their NADPH levels and leads to the accumulation of

140
00:08:32.212 --> 00:08:36.033
cysteine. We have found that the accumulation of cysteine

141
00:08:36.052 --> 00:08:38.232
within the cell can be toxic as well.

142
00:08:38.312 --> 00:08:41.832
Cysteine stabilizes an enzyme called CDO1, which

143
00:08:42.252 --> 00:08:45.572
catalyzes the irreversible metabolism of cysteine to taurine.

144
00:08:46.032 --> 00:08:49.872
And so in non-small cell lung cancer cells, this not only produces

145
00:08:49.892 --> 00:08:53.872
taurine, but some toxic intermediates downstream in the taurine synthesis

146
00:08:53.972 --> 00:08:57.892
pathway, and also leads to the depletion of NADPH

147
00:08:58.092 --> 00:09:01.752
as the non-small cell lung cancer cells are continually trying to replenish the

148
00:09:01.772 --> 00:09:05.152
cysteine pool. So non-small cell lung cancer cells evade this

149
00:09:05.172 --> 00:09:08.012
vulnerability by epigenetically silencing CDO1.

150
00:09:10.452 --> 00:09:11.872
And finally, when

151
00:09:13.152 --> 00:09:17.112
glucose uptake is inhibited and NADPH is depleted, the cysteine

152
00:09:17.132 --> 00:09:20.852
that accumulates leads to formation of aberrant disulfide

153
00:09:20.912 --> 00:09:24.892
bridges in the actin cytoskeleton, leading to a different form of cell death

154
00:09:25.032 --> 00:09:28.932
called disulfidatosis. And this is recently described by Boyu Gan's

155
00:09:28.952 --> 00:09:32.572
lab. So there's really a lot of ways that Nrf2 activation

156
00:09:32.612 --> 00:09:34.992
confers different metabolic vulnerabilities.

157
00:09:36.912 --> 00:09:40.502
But there's one new one. So this is work from Lucas O'Sullivan's lab that's brand

158
00:09:40.532 --> 00:09:42.652
new, just came out, I think, two weeks ago.

159
00:09:43.212 --> 00:09:46.912
And they found that cysteine, in addition to these other toxic outputs of

160
00:09:46.952 --> 00:09:50.672
cysteine that have previously been described, also forms adducts within cells.

161
00:09:51.292 --> 00:09:54.852
And so in addition to some reversible conjugates that can be

162
00:09:55.452 --> 00:09:59.432
formed within cells like that with pyruvate, it can also form irreversible

163
00:09:59.492 --> 00:10:03.132
adducts with some intermediates in the glycolytic pathway to form these

164
00:10:03.152 --> 00:10:05.502
cysteine sugar adducts, which can be toxic.

165
00:10:06.032 --> 00:10:09.792
So the accumulation of too much cysteine within

166
00:10:09.812 --> 00:10:13.072
cells with Nrf2 activation can also be detrimental.

167
00:10:13.432 --> 00:10:17.032
So there's really a fine balance between having too much cysteine and too little

168
00:10:17.072 --> 00:10:18.292
cysteine within cells.

169
00:10:21.291 --> 00:10:25.222
So a lot of the work that I've told you about has been performed in cell culture,

170
00:10:25.552 --> 00:10:29.532
where we're giving cells really a lot of cysteine or starving them

171
00:10:29.572 --> 00:10:33.012
completely. But in vivo, the situation is more complicated.

172
00:10:33.032 --> 00:10:37.022
There may be nutrient gradients. Cells are very rarely completely starved or

173
00:10:37.052 --> 00:10:39.682
given extreme excesses of nutrients.

174
00:10:40.112 --> 00:10:43.572
So we're really interested in understanding what is the source of cysteine in vivo

175
00:10:43.592 --> 00:10:47.072
and how is it used, and how does that depend on how much is available.

176
00:10:47.752 --> 00:10:51.062
And so I told you a lot about xCT. This pathway is regulated by

177
00:10:51.092 --> 00:10:54.672
Nrf2. But there are other ways to get cysteine, and one of these is the

178
00:10:54.692 --> 00:10:57.992
transsulfuration pathway, in which methionine donates the

179
00:10:58.012 --> 00:11:00.592
sulfur and serine donates the carbon backbone.

180
00:11:01.012 --> 00:11:04.292
And this pathway is very active in the liver, but its

181
00:11:04.352 --> 00:11:08.212
contribution to cysteine in other tissues and within tumors is

182
00:11:08.252 --> 00:11:10.252
really not well understood.

183
00:11:11.152 --> 00:11:14.452
Cysteine could technically be imported directly

184
00:11:15.192 --> 00:11:18.812
through cysteine transporters. Their identity is not very well understood.

185
00:11:19.332 --> 00:11:22.992
And in our cell culture media, cysteine is completely absent, and it's

186
00:11:23.052 --> 00:11:26.532
also lacking in our blood as well. So how much cysteine is actually

187
00:11:26.572 --> 00:11:29.512
available to tumor cells is pretty underappreciated.

188
00:11:31.132 --> 00:11:33.612
And so we wanted to understand this in vivo.

189
00:11:33.752 --> 00:11:37.512
So we use a variety of different genetically engineered mouse models.

190
00:11:37.552 --> 00:11:41.462
And I'm just showing you two, I think that highlight the diversity

191
00:11:41.552 --> 00:11:45.232
of the activity of this pathway. So first starting with the liver, we

192
00:11:45.632 --> 00:11:49.112
used a hydrodynamic tail vein injection model to overexpress Myc and delete

193
00:11:49.132 --> 00:11:49.912
p53

194
00:11:50.812 --> 00:11:54.772
and compare liver tumors that form to a

195
00:11:54.812 --> 00:11:58.452
normal healthy liver. And so we used carbon-13 labeled serine that we

196
00:11:58.492 --> 00:12:01.972
infused into mice and then looked at labeling in cysteine.

197
00:12:02.692 --> 00:12:05.612
So what we found was that normal liver had activation of this

198
00:12:05.672 --> 00:12:09.262
pathway. And when we compared the tumors, we found that there

199
00:12:09.262 --> 00:12:12.812
wasPretty similar labeling. There was slightly less in the liver tumors,

200
00:12:13.132 --> 00:12:15.981
but all tumors had some detectable cysteine production.

201
00:12:16.382 --> 00:12:18.932
And we could follow that into glutathione synthesis by looking at

202
00:12:18.972 --> 00:12:22.752
gamma-glutamylcysteine. When we looked at the

203
00:12:22.812 --> 00:12:26.562
lung, though, we found that the lung had no detectable labeling in cysteine from

204
00:12:26.572 --> 00:12:29.352
serine, so no transsulfuration activity.

205
00:12:29.372 --> 00:12:33.152
And when we looked at two different lung cancer models, one driven by a mutation in

206
00:12:33.192 --> 00:12:37.112
KRAS and loss of p53, and then another similar model where we added in

207
00:12:37.152 --> 00:12:40.932
a Nrf2 mutation, we found that lung tumors did not gain the

208
00:12:40.952 --> 00:12:42.191
ability to make cysteine.

209
00:12:43.172 --> 00:12:47.092
And not surprisingly, because they didn't make cysteine, there was no labeling

210
00:12:47.132 --> 00:12:48.832
in the glutathione synthesis pathway.

211
00:12:50.012 --> 00:12:53.692
So we would predict based on this data that lung tumors would likely be very

212
00:12:53.732 --> 00:12:56.232
dependent on uptake of exogenous cystine,

213
00:12:57.132 --> 00:12:57.912
whereas liver,

214
00:12:59.272 --> 00:13:01.771
because they can make their own cysteine, maybe would be less dependent.

215
00:13:02.432 --> 00:13:06.132
But we wanted to know how much cysteine is labeled from the circulation.

216
00:13:06.532 --> 00:13:09.592
So we repeated this experiment and infused mice with labeled cystine.

217
00:13:10.832 --> 00:13:14.491
And what we found was that when we did that, the normal

218
00:13:14.532 --> 00:13:18.512
liver could also take up circulating cystine and label the cysteine pool,

219
00:13:18.972 --> 00:13:20.312
and the liver tumors could as well.

220
00:13:20.372 --> 00:13:24.192
Although again, we saw a slight decrease in the tumors suggesting there was maybe

221
00:13:24.292 --> 00:13:28.132
contribution from an unlabeled cysteine source, maybe glutathione,

222
00:13:28.172 --> 00:13:29.972
like Isaac reported, maybe something else.

223
00:13:30.922 --> 00:13:33.552
And we could follow that into glutathione synthesis.

224
00:13:34.072 --> 00:13:37.362
Whereas in the lung, we only saw labeling from cystine in the cysteine

225
00:13:37.452 --> 00:13:41.292
pool with no real difference between lung and the two different lung tumor

226
00:13:41.332 --> 00:13:44.852
models. But when we looked at glutathione labeling, that's where we really saw a

227
00:13:44.892 --> 00:13:48.772
difference with a progressive increase when we went from lung to the lung

228
00:13:48.852 --> 00:13:52.752
tumor model to the Nrf2 mutant lung tumor model, consistent with what we know about

229
00:13:52.792 --> 00:13:54.792
Nrf2 promoting glutathione synthesis.

230
00:13:56.132 --> 00:13:59.692
So from this, we would predict that if we blocked cystine uptake, this would be

231
00:14:00.352 --> 00:14:04.192
very potent to a lung tumor model, maybe less potent to a

232
00:14:04.232 --> 00:14:05.212
liver cancer model.

233
00:14:07.432 --> 00:14:11.092
One caveat to our study, though, was that when we infused the mice with uniformly

234
00:14:11.212 --> 00:14:14.872
labeled cystine, it formed mixed disulfides in the circulation.

235
00:14:15.332 --> 00:14:18.832
So the cystine may be entering into the tumors or the

236
00:14:18.892 --> 00:14:22.612
tissues as cysteine. We can't really distinguish from our methods.

237
00:14:25.512 --> 00:14:28.672
So we spent a lot of time trying to target

238
00:14:29.312 --> 00:14:32.692
cystine transport or the circulating cysteine pool,

239
00:14:33.272 --> 00:14:36.692
and we had some technical issues with cystinase, which degrades

240
00:14:38.372 --> 00:14:41.712
