00:27:39.522 --> 00:27:43.462
cell will reprogram to use other amino acid as a source to compensate

486
00:27:43.472 --> 00:27:47.182
this blocking effect. And the second one is that do you confirm whether the cancer

487
00:27:47.242 --> 00:27:50.242
cell, they will be able to produce, or other cell in the tumor microenvironment

488
00:27:50.262 --> 00:27:51.792
will produce cysteine?

489
00:27:52.702 --> 00:27:56.442
So for the first question, our lung cancer cells don't

490
00:27:56.502 --> 00:28:00.112
make cysteine, so we haven't done any work blocking cysteine

491
00:28:00.182 --> 00:28:02.202
synthesis because they naturally just don't do it.

492
00:28:02.282 --> 00:28:06.262
We've done tracing in the cell lines too, and we see absolutely zero labeling

493
00:28:06.282 --> 00:28:09.922
in cysteine. For the second, in terms of cells in the microenvironment, we've

494
00:28:09.962 --> 00:28:12.962
started looking at that, looking at the ability of

495
00:28:13.522 --> 00:28:16.682
macrophages that we isolate from the model, CAFs that we isolate from the model,

496
00:28:16.742 --> 00:28:20.662
and their ability to secrete cysteine, and we see that macrophages do have a

497
00:28:20.702 --> 00:28:24.562
contribution. And if we co-culture our lung cancer cells with macrophages, it will

498
00:28:24.622 --> 00:28:28.582
rescue erastin treatment. So we think that they are at least one of

499
00:28:28.622 --> 00:28:31.682
the contributing factors. We don't think they're a major contributor to the

500
00:28:31.722 --> 00:28:34.062
glutathione, though, and we're still trying to figure out what's going on with

501
00:28:34.282 --> 00:28:35.802
glutathione and where that's coming from.

502
00:28:36.282 --> 00:28:36.502
So-

503
00:28:37.282 --> 00:28:37.482
That's good

504
00:28:37.842 --> 00:28:38.182
... thank you.

505
00:28:38.762 --> 00:28:40.702
Okay. Thank you.

506
00:28:45.902 --> 00:28:49.802
Okay, so I'm this next speaker. I just forgot to introduce myself

507
00:28:50.262 --> 00:28:53.102
in the beginning of the section. I'm the chair of the section and also speaker of

508
00:28:53.142 --> 00:28:55.582
this section. I'm Ping-Chi Ho from Lausanne, Switzerland.

509
00:28:56.322 --> 00:28:57.362
So today, I'll talk about

510
00:28:58.222 --> 00:29:02.142
T cell behavior in the tumor microenvironment and how the metabolic process

511
00:29:02.162 --> 00:29:05.502
happening in the tumor microenvironment will be able to affect T cell behavior.

512
00:29:06.042 --> 00:29:09.662
So as I mentioned in the introduction of the section, we will cover

513
00:29:09.722 --> 00:29:11.982
cancer, T cell, and also macrophage.

514
00:29:13.202 --> 00:29:13.602
Okay, so

515
00:29:14.762 --> 00:29:16.122
I would like to switch the gear a little bit.

516
00:29:16.162 --> 00:29:19.622
So before I go through all the experimental detail, I want to let you know what is

517
00:29:19.661 --> 00:29:22.482
the T cell differentiation happening in the tumor microenvironment.

518
00:29:22.502 --> 00:29:26.302
So here which is very different from the viral infection or acute stimulation.

519
00:29:26.322 --> 00:29:29.522
We know that in response to chronic antigen happening in the tumor

520
00:29:29.562 --> 00:29:32.752
microenvironment, CD8 T cell, they will differentiate in a very different manner.

521
00:29:33.242 --> 00:29:37.002
So they will start to have a stem-like property, and this is the population that

522
00:29:37.042 --> 00:29:38.462
will sit there, and then do self-renew.

523
00:29:38.502 --> 00:29:41.742
They can also respond to immune checkpoint blockade treatment.

524
00:29:42.042 --> 00:29:45.762
They highly express several surface marker at the same time, the expression of

525
00:29:45.802 --> 00:29:49.642
FOXO1, BACH2, and TCF1, those transcription factor

526
00:29:49.682 --> 00:29:51.182
can control their stemness property.

527
00:29:51.582 --> 00:29:55.502
Unfortunately, in response to chronic antigen exposure, those T cells

528
00:29:55.522 --> 00:29:59.362
will start to lose this expression, and they start to express

529
00:29:59.382 --> 00:30:03.192
BLIMP1, EPHB2, those factors which can control effector function,

530
00:30:03.682 --> 00:30:07.582
even push the T cell into so-called terminal exhausted T cell condition.

531
00:30:08.082 --> 00:30:09.982
And this will completely change the T cell quality.

532
00:30:10.012 --> 00:30:13.222
At the same time, T cell fail to respond to PD-1 blockade treatments.

533
00:30:13.522 --> 00:30:17.342
They also down-regulates the ability to proliferate, to produce cytokine.

534
00:30:17.682 --> 00:30:21.542
And this represent one of the major problem for our cancer immunotherapy, because

535
00:30:21.602 --> 00:30:25.442
our T cell with the best T cell receptor to recognize those

536
00:30:25.482 --> 00:30:29.032
neoantigen expressed by cancer cells, they mainly go through this

537
00:30:29.062 --> 00:30:30.862
process and become dysfunctional T cell.

538
00:30:31.302 --> 00:30:35.222
So if we understand the process, we might be able to develop treatments to either

539
00:30:35.231 --> 00:30:38.662
prevent the commitment of T cell exhaustion or restore the

540
00:30:38.702 --> 00:30:39.982
functionality of those T cell.

541
00:30:41.142 --> 00:30:44.922
So a few years ago, when I was a postdoc at Yale, I proposed

542
00:30:44.962 --> 00:30:48.902
that in the tumor microenvironment when T cell infiltrate, they will start to fight

543
00:30:48.942 --> 00:30:52.682
against cancer cells. However, T cell, when they proliferate, when they produce

544
00:30:52.722 --> 00:30:56.702
cytokine, they need to use a lot of glucose and go through glycolysis pathway to

545
00:30:56.742 --> 00:30:58.522
maintain their expansion like cancer cells.

546
00:30:59.162 --> 00:31:03.122
But due to the metabolic restriction and also the high metabolic activity of cancer

547
00:31:03.142 --> 00:31:07.042
cells, you can consider some of the tumor types you will see very low level of

548
00:31:07.062 --> 00:31:09.082
glucose in a tumor interstitial fluid.

549
00:31:09.622 --> 00:31:12.152
In this case, T cell will not be able to get sufficient glucose.

550
00:31:12.722 --> 00:31:15.582
However, we also know that those T cells still can hang there.

551
00:31:15.662 --> 00:31:18.462
They can still survive. So it raise a very important question.

552
00:31:18.982 --> 00:31:22.082
This probably is a condition those T cell need to engage metabolic

553
00:31:22.222 --> 00:31:26.104
adaptation. They will start to survive.So as everyone learned in the

554
00:31:26.174 --> 00:31:30.014
biochemistry textbook, mitochondria is one of the major organelle

555
00:31:30.054 --> 00:31:33.114
in our cells which can help the metabolic adaptation.

556
00:31:33.494 --> 00:31:36.454
So if you don't have glucose, once you have mitochondria activity, you can start to

557
00:31:36.474 --> 00:31:39.274
burn fats, you can start to use amino acid as a nutrient.

558
00:31:39.674 --> 00:31:43.124
So at that time, we speculate maybe those CD8 T-cell in the tumor microenvironment,

559
00:31:43.174 --> 00:31:46.414
they cannot get sufficient glucose, but they start to increase their mitochondria

560
00:31:46.454 --> 00:31:48.454
activity to maintain their survival.

561
00:31:48.994 --> 00:31:52.974
So we isolate CD8 T-cell from tumor-bearing mice, either from tumor

562
00:31:53.014 --> 00:31:55.574
or spleen, and we perform electron microscopy analysis.

563
00:31:55.614 --> 00:31:59.414
As you can see here, we indeed see increase of mitochondria content in those CD8

564
00:31:59.424 --> 00:32:01.404
T-cell infiltrate into the tumor microenvironment.

565
00:32:01.784 --> 00:32:05.334
However, my postdoc, Iru, did the analysis to check whether we can see the

566
00:32:05.354 --> 00:32:08.214
mitochondrial DNA copy number increase. We didn't see that.

567
00:32:08.534 --> 00:32:10.214
So this raise a very important question.

568
00:32:10.734 --> 00:32:13.914
Most of the CD8 T-cell, they infiltrate into the tumor microenvironment.

569
00:32:13.924 --> 00:32:17.014
They start to increase their mitochondria based upon the morphology.

570
00:32:17.034 --> 00:32:20.574
But probably those mitochondria they have actually lose the integrity to

571
00:32:20.634 --> 00:32:24.454
maintain mitochondrial DNA copy number, and which is very common for aging

572
00:32:24.534 --> 00:32:24.854
cells.

573
00:32:25.874 --> 00:32:29.614
So at that time, we proposed this idea, maybe this is a default setting.

574
00:32:29.694 --> 00:32:32.734
When every single T-cell go into the tumor microenvironment, they will start to

575
00:32:32.794 --> 00:32:35.834
encounter metabolic stress happening in the tumor microenvironment.

576
00:32:36.214 --> 00:32:40.114
This lead to gradually increase of damaged mitochondria or depolarized mitochondria

577
00:32:40.514 --> 00:32:42.214
stay in the cytoplasm of those T-cell.

578
00:32:42.574 --> 00:32:45.934
They will not be able to remove them, and this can promote T-cell dysfunction.

579
00:32:46.354 --> 00:32:50.194
At the same time, Craig Thompson and also Gregg DeGoeffe, they also report the

580
00:32:50.274 --> 00:32:53.814
same thing. And these three paper published almost in a three-month period

581
00:32:54.234 --> 00:32:54.314
to

582
00:32:55.614 --> 00:32:56.114
reveal this

583
00:32:57.054 --> 00:33:01.014
process. Unfortunately, none of the paper really disclosed

584
00:33:01.254 --> 00:33:05.234
the underlying mechanism. So my other postdoc decide to work into the detail

585
00:33:05.254 --> 00:33:08.834
to understand what happened, and we'll probably be able to

586
00:33:08.854 --> 00:33:11.594
generate the therapeutic approach to prevent this process.

587
00:33:12.654 --> 00:33:14.314
So that's come back what happened.

588
00:33:14.794 --> 00:33:17.664
So we know that in a tumor microenvironment is glucose-deprived condition.

589
00:33:18.014 --> 00:33:20.754
So for cells, they need to survive, they need to increase the mitochondria

590
00:33:20.794 --> 00:33:22.734
activity, increase the mitochondrial biogenesis.

591
00:33:22.814 --> 00:33:26.244
However, there's another metabolic stress happening in the tumor microenvironment,

592
00:33:26.294 --> 00:33:30.224
which is hypoxia. So basically, those CD8 T-cell, they need to run oxidative

593
00:33:30.274 --> 00:33:32.634
metabolism in low oxygen condition.

594
00:33:32.714 --> 00:33:36.423
This can damage their mitochondria due to robust mitochondrial

595
00:33:36.554 --> 00:33:39.994
ROS production. And normally this is fine because we can use

596
00:33:40.034 --> 00:33:42.114
mitophagy to get rid of damaged mitochondria.

597
00:33:42.154 --> 00:33:45.814
However, those T-cell in tumor, they also see very strong T-cell

598
00:33:45.854 --> 00:33:49.614
receptor signal which can activate MTOR and block autophagy and

599
00:33:49.634 --> 00:33:52.934
mitophagy. So in that case, they enter to a perfect storm.

600
00:33:52.994 --> 00:33:54.793
In one end, they damage their mitochondria.

601
00:33:54.954 --> 00:33:57.174
On the other hand, they cannot remove the damaged mitochondria.

602
00:33:57.734 --> 00:34:01.274
And this is very dangerous because you still have those damaged mitochondria, you

603
00:34:01.314 --> 00:34:05.054
still have those mitochondrial protein in a damaged organelle.

604
00:34:05.624 --> 00:34:09.394
So we speculate those cells, in order to survive, when they accumulate

605
00:34:09.415 --> 00:34:12.774
damaged mitochondria, they need to engage other homeostasis

606
00:34:12.834 --> 00:34:16.234
pathway to dampen the mitochondria activity.

607
00:34:16.435 --> 00:34:20.194
Otherwise, those damaged mitochondria will start to create different or

608
00:34:20.554 --> 00:34:24.294
unwanted biochemical reaction, further damage the cells.

609
00:34:25.334 --> 00:34:27.064
So we decide to take a look at what happens.

610
00:34:27.134 --> 00:34:30.894
So basically, we isolated the CD8 T-cell in a tumor microenvironment based upon

611
00:34:30.935 --> 00:34:34.754
their mitochondria staining. So we can use MitoTrack Green to stain the

612
00:34:34.794 --> 00:34:38.394
mitochondria mass and MitoTrack Deep Red to stain the mitochondria membrane

613
00:34:38.415 --> 00:34:42.314
potential. As you can see here, this population we call MDR, MDR low.

614
00:34:42.374 --> 00:34:46.254
They contain more mitochondria, but most of the mitochondria are depolarized.

615
00:34:46.274 --> 00:34:49.034
And this is the T-cell subset. They are dysfunction.

616
00:34:49.354 --> 00:34:51.554
They have a lot of exhaustion phenotype.

617
00:34:52.354 --> 00:34:55.745
And by comparing the RNA sequencing data between the functional

618
00:34:55.794 --> 00:34:59.334
mitochondria-containing T-cell versus those T-cell accumulate damaged mitochondria,

619
00:34:59.814 --> 00:35:02.814
we start to see a lot of metabolic process start to change.

620
00:35:03.194 --> 00:35:06.934
Among those metabolic process, proteasome is the one which related to

621
00:35:06.974 --> 00:35:10.934
homeostasis robustly increase in those T-cell accumulate

622
00:35:10.994 --> 00:35:14.294
damaged mitochondria. And in the beginning, we don't really understand what

623
00:35:14.394 --> 00:35:16.254
happened. What's the reason you can see that?

624
00:35:16.974 --> 00:35:19.994
And we decide to take a look whether we can really see the mitochondrial protein

625
00:35:20.014 --> 00:35:23.754
degradation. So Yingxi did a very interesting and very smart

626
00:35:23.814 --> 00:35:27.754
design. So basically, we just fuse the mCherry reporter with a amino

627
00:35:27.814 --> 00:35:30.934
acid sequence. This is a Dron sequence which can receive

628
00:35:31.234 --> 00:35:35.134
polyubiquitylation. Once you have a polyubiquitylation, this entire mCherry

629
00:35:35.154 --> 00:35:37.734
will be degraded, so you will lose the mCherry reporter.

630
00:35:38.354 --> 00:35:42.314
So basically, we use this Dron system and tag with the signal peptide

631
00:35:42.374 --> 00:35:46.214
to make this entire fusion reporter either tag into the cytoplasm

632
00:35:46.774 --> 00:35:50.434
or into the mitochondria. So we can monitor whether the degradation can

633
00:35:50.494 --> 00:35:54.134
happen in a specific location. By using this method, we

634
00:35:54.174 --> 00:35:57.894
realize that those T-cell accumulate damaged mitochondria, if we

635
00:35:57.914 --> 00:36:01.394
block their protein synthesis, you can see the stability of this

636
00:36:01.494 --> 00:36:05.134
mCherry. Those low population tend to degrade mitochondria

637
00:36:05.194 --> 00:36:09.134
reporter way more efficiently compared with the T-cell

638
00:36:09.174 --> 00:36:10.514
that still have functional mitochondria.

639
00:36:10.954 --> 00:36:14.054
But if you check their cytosolic Dron reporter, nothing happened.

640
00:36:14.094 --> 00:36:15.894
They have a similar degradation kinetics.

641
00:36:16.414 --> 00:36:19.854
So this result indicates that when those T-cell accumulate damaged

642
00:36:19.894 --> 00:36:23.794
mitochondria in a tumor microenvironment, they cannot remove damaged mitochondria.

643
00:36:23.874 --> 00:36:25.994
They start to degrade mitochondria protein.

644
00:36:26.034 --> 00:36:30.014
They use this approach to prevent those damaged mitochondria keeping

645
00:36:30.034 --> 00:36:32.054
doing wrong biochemical reaction.

646
00:36:33.454 --> 00:36:37.394
So we also realize that this can happen in human, because once we generate human

647
00:36:37.414 --> 00:36:40.894
T-cell, they become progenitor with a stemness property or terminal exhausted

648
00:36:40.934 --> 00:36:44.844
T-cell. You can also appreciate that those terminal exhausted T-cell tend to

649
00:36:44.914 --> 00:36:48.194
degrade mitochondria reporter way more efficient than their counterpart.

650
00:36:48.614 --> 00:36:50.234
In cytosolic Dron, nothing change.

651
00:36:51.914 --> 00:36:54.994
So with this information, we start to wonder, maybe that's true.

652
00:36:55.054 --> 00:36:58.624
We see the RNA sequencing pattern, we see the protein degradation reporter system,

653
00:36:58.714 --> 00:37:01.874
but we want to know what kind of protein those T-cell accumulate damaged

654
00:37:01.894 --> 00:37:05.414
mitochondria indeed degrade. So we perform similar analysis.

655
00:37:05.514 --> 00:37:09.474
We isolate those T-cell based upon their mitochondria activity, and then we treat

656
00:37:09.484 --> 00:37:13.454
them with either control vehicle or cycloheximide to prevent new synthesis of

657
00:37:13.494 --> 00:37:17.234
protein. And then we subject them to proteomic analysis to

658
00:37:17.314 --> 00:37:21.274
identify which protein was selectively degraded by comparing the control

659
00:37:21.314 --> 00:37:25.034
versus CHK treated one. So as you can see on the right-hand

660
00:37:25.134 --> 00:37:27.574
side, those T-cell accumulate damaged mitochondria.

661
00:37:27.674 --> 00:37:31.070
They degrade tons of protein in the mitochondria.It can be out of membrane, in the

662
00:37:31.130 --> 00:37:33.110
membrane, complex one, complex five, you name it.

663
00:37:33.650 --> 00:37:36.450
They tend to degrade mitochondrial protein, not only the reporter.

664
00:37:36.910 --> 00:37:40.570
So we confirm this is true. They tend to degrade mitochondrial protein when they

665
00:37:40.610 --> 00:37:43.510
cannot use mitophagy to remove damaged mitochondria.

666
00:37:44.570 --> 00:37:48.450
And by using this method, we can also confirm in other type by using human

667
00:37:48.490 --> 00:37:51.830
T cell, we also see the same thing. In a human T cell, if they have damaged

668
00:37:51.870 --> 00:37:55.010
mitochondria accumulation, they also get rid of mitochondrial protein way more

669
00:37:55.070 --> 00:37:55.620
efficiently.

670
00:37:57.090 --> 00:38:00.810
And one thing we also noticed by analyzing what kind of protein get degraded, we

671
00:38:00.850 --> 00:38:04.470
realized that a lot of protein, this T cell accumulate damaged

672
00:38:04.490 --> 00:38:07.550
mitochondria can degrade. They are hemoprotein.

673
00:38:07.570 --> 00:38:10.930
They are mitochondrial protein. They have the biochemical reaction

674
00:38:11.190 --> 00:38:12.930
activity when they bind with heme.

675
00:38:13.750 --> 00:38:17.590
So if this is true, when T cells start to degrade those protein,

676
00:38:17.690 --> 00:38:21.560
you can see those heme become freely available because they will

677
00:38:21.610 --> 00:38:25.290
be released in the cytoplasm. They will start to bind to other

678
00:38:25.350 --> 00:38:28.730
protein in the wrong cellular compartment to regulate cellular behavior.

679
00:38:29.430 --> 00:38:32.690
So we decide to use another approach to confirm what happened.

680
00:38:32.730 --> 00:38:36.350
So basically, we need to have a method which allowed us to monitor

681
00:38:36.450 --> 00:38:38.970
freely available heme. And this is very simple.

682
00:38:39.030 --> 00:38:42.770
We just need to use HRP. Most people use in the Western blot.

683
00:38:43.330 --> 00:38:46.740
HRP actually is a hemoprotein. So we just need to purchase the commercially

684
00:38:46.830 --> 00:38:50.770
available HRP and treat the HRP with acetone to make this HRP

685
00:38:50.810 --> 00:38:54.270
become apo HRP. And we can incubate the apo

686
00:38:54.390 --> 00:38:58.010
HRP with the cell lysate derived from T cell with damaged

687
00:38:58.030 --> 00:39:01.250
mitochondria or functional mitochondria. So we use three method.

688
00:39:01.330 --> 00:39:05.270
The first method is that mouse T cell, we give them mitophagy inhibitor

689
00:39:05.310 --> 00:39:07.150
plus oligomycin A and antimycin A.

690
00:39:07.730 --> 00:39:10.130
This can promote the accumulation of damaged mitochondria.

691
00:39:10.660 --> 00:39:14.460
And the second method is a tumor cell conditional medium plus TCR stimulation and

692
00:39:14.510 --> 00:39:17.090
hypoxia to mimic a tumor microenvironment.

693
00:39:17.490 --> 00:39:20.790
In both method, those T cell accumulate damaged mitochondria.

694
00:39:21.110 --> 00:39:23.270
They start to increase freely available heme.

695
00:39:24.050 --> 00:39:25.560
We call them regulatory heme.

696
00:39:26.490 --> 00:39:30.410
And the other one is a human T cell. We give them NY-ESO TCR, and then

697
00:39:30.450 --> 00:39:33.690
we pattern the stimulation to mimic what happened in the tumor microenvironment.

698
00:39:33.970 --> 00:39:35.869
They also accumulate damaged mitochondria.

699
00:39:36.250 --> 00:39:38.530
They also tend to increase freely available heme.

700
00:39:39.190 --> 00:39:43.150
So overall, our data suggests that this is a common mechanism can happen in both

701
00:39:43.210 --> 00:39:46.810
mouse and human T cell. So when they start to accumulate damaged

702
00:39:46.830 --> 00:39:50.370
mitochondria, they would try to polyubiquitinate those

703
00:39:50.470 --> 00:39:54.250
mitochondrial protein to ship them into the cytoplasm and then

704
00:39:54.350 --> 00:39:56.590
degrade them through the proteasome activity.

705
00:39:57.210 --> 00:40:00.270
And once those protein degraded, heme will become freely available.

706
00:40:00.990 --> 00:40:04.770
But one thing we have to do, as many researchers need to do, is that we

707
00:40:04.830 --> 00:40:07.590
have to have the positive and negative control in our assay.

708
00:40:08.030 --> 00:40:11.930
So I told Yingxi, maybe we should try to have a positive assay or negative assay to

709
00:40:11.990 --> 00:40:15.890
confirm this regulatory heme measurement

710
00:40:15.930 --> 00:40:19.530
is holding true. It's real. We are not just monitor something else.

711
00:40:20.270 --> 00:40:24.110
So the real control we should do is that we should block

712
00:40:24.170 --> 00:40:27.850
proteasome activity to see whether we can see the reduction of the

713
00:40:27.910 --> 00:40:30.710
measurement. So that's what she did.

714
00:40:31.330 --> 00:40:35.109
So she treat the cells with MG132. As you can see, both

715
00:40:35.570 --> 00:40:39.070
T cell with functional mitochondria or T cell with damaged mitochondria, once you

716
00:40:39.150 --> 00:40:42.930
treat them with proteasome inhibitor, Avidin decrease.

717
00:40:42.990 --> 00:40:46.390
Okay, so this means our measurement indeed is true.

718
00:40:46.410 --> 00:40:50.270
But something is quite interesting because we start to realize

719
00:40:50.350 --> 00:40:54.010
when you treat the cells with MG132, those T cell

720
00:40:54.050 --> 00:40:56.730
